    <div class="rlo-content-body">
        Gamma (&#947;) rays are a form of ionizing electromagnetic radiation, 
        and so are uncharged  (unlike alpha and beta radiation). A gamma photon 
        is a packet of electromagnetic energy  emitted from a nucleus. &#947; ray 
        photons from <strong>nuclear decay</strong> have energies in the range 
        ~100keV â€¦10MeV.
        <br/><br/>
        Often following the decay of a parent nuclide (by &#945;, &#946; or EC), 
        a daughter nuclide is left in an excited state 
